<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900511-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>900511-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Aide of McDade   Is Indicted in Case   Tied to Defense Firm   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>05/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14</SO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Federal prosecutors investigating Rep.Joseph McDade (R., Pa.) obtained an indictment charging thelawmaker's former top aide with racketeering, conspiracy andtax violations.   The eight felony charges against Raymond Wittig, Rep.McDade's primary link to a minority defense contractor,indicate that prosecutors have stepped up their inquiry intowhether the veteran GOP lawmaker accepted illegal campaigncontributions and gratuities from officials of the company.</LP><TEXT>   In the Philadelphia federal court indictment, Mr. Wittigwas charged, among other things, with conspiring to funnelbribes and gratuities to public officials who helped thenow-defunct United Chem-Con Corp. secure and maintain federalcontracts over the years. The indictment doesn't identify anyof those officials, but some of the charges parallelallegations against the congressman first raised in aDecember 1988 front-page story in The Wall Street Journal.   Rep. McDade, Mr. Wittig and their lawyers couldn't bereached for comment. In the past, Rep. McDade has maintainedthat he hasn't violated any laws and said his efforts onbehalf of United Chem-Con were intended to keep jobs in hisdistrict. Mr. Wittig has acknowledged soliciting campaigngifts and other favors for Rep. McDade from companyofficials, but has denied any wrongdoing.   Assistant U.S. Attorney Nicholas Harbist, who has headedthe two-year Philadelphia grand jury investigation, said onlythat the inquiry is continuing.   If convicted on all counts, Mr. Wittig faces a maximum of41 years in jail and a $1.4 million fine.</TEXT></DOC>